You can do it with a very little bit of math: you can get the last four bits of your byte with `b % 16`, and the first four with integer division by 16. Then you just have to combine both parts.

Note that you get integers when indexing/iterating on a bytes object.

So:

    test=b&quot;\x05\x08\x06\x04\x01\x05&quot; 
    result=b&quot;\x50\x80\x60\x40\x10&quot;
    
    out = bytes((test[i]%16)*16 + test[i+1]//16 for i in range(len(test)-1))
    print((out))
    # b&#39;P\x80`@\x10&#39;

(As some values match the ASCII codes of printable characters, these characters are printed here instead of the `\x..` representation)

